A historical photograph captures an Amherst College "Lord Jeffs" versus [Cornell ice hockey](/Cornell_Big_Red_men%27s_ice_hockey) game on [Beebe Lake](/Beebe_Lake_(Ithaca,_New_York)), Ithaca, on January 14, 1922.

Amherst College actively participates in the [National Collegiate Athletic Association's](/National_Collegiate_Athletic_Association) [Division III](/NCAA_Division_III), the [Eastern College Athletic Conference](/Eastern_College_Athletic_Conference), and the [New England Small College Athletic Conference](/New_England_Small_College_Athletic_Conference). The NESCAC comprises [Bates](/Bates_College), [Bowdoin](/Bowdoin_College), [Colby](/Colby_College), [Connecticut College](/Connecticut_College), [Hamilton](/Hamilton_College), [Middlebury](/Middlebury_College), [Trinity](/Trinity_College_(Connecticut)), [Tufts](/Tufts_University), [Wesleyan](/Wesleyan_University), and [Williams](/Williams_College). Amherst is also a proud member of the "[Little Three](/Little_Three)," alongside Williams and Wesleyan. While an informal Little Three champion is often recognized based on head-to-head records, formal three-way competitions are held in certain sports.

Amherst proudly claims its athletics program as the oldest in the nation, citing the implementation of a compulsory physical fitness regimen in 1860. Although the mandate for all students to participate in sports or physical education has since been discontinued, this historical precedent underscores the college's long-standing commitment to athletic development. Amherst and Williams played what is widely recognized as the first [college baseball](/College_baseball) game on July 2, 1859.

In recent years, Amherst's burgeoning athletics program has become a subject of discussion and analysis due to perceived disparities in the racial and socioeconomic composition of its student athletes compared to the broader student body. Furthermore, concerns have been raised regarding the concentration of athletes within specific academic departments and a perceived divide on campus between varsity athletes and other students. Athletic prowess is a recognized factor in admissions decisions, influencing between 28% and 35% of each incoming class.

Amherst also fields a variety of [club athletic teams](/Collegiate_club_sports_in_the_United_States), including [ultimate](/Ultimate_(sport)), soccer, crew, [rugby union](/Rugby_union), [water polo](/Water_polo), [equestrian](/Equestrianism), [mountain biking](/Mountain_biking), [fencing](/Fencing), [sailing](/Sailing_(sport)), and skiing. The college also offers [intramural sports](/Intramural_sports) such as soccer, tennis, golf, basketball, volleyball, and softball, providing ample opportunities for athletic engagement across the student body.

The sport of Ultimate was notably originated and named at Amherst College in the mid-1960s by Jared Kass, marking a significant contribution to the world of recreational sports.

Alumni

*   *Main article: [List of Amherst College people](/List_of_Amherst_College_people)*

Despite its relatively small size, Amherst College has produced an extraordinary number of accomplished alumni. Its graduates include recipients of [Nobel Prizes](/Nobel_Prize), the [Crafoord Prize](/Crafoord_Prize), and the [Lasker Award](/Lasker_Award), as well as winners of [MacArthur Fellowships](/MacArthur_Fellows_Program) and [Pulitzer Prizes](/Pulitzer_Prize). The college's alumni have also received the [National Medal of Science](/National_Medal_of_Science) and the [National Book Award](/National_Book_Award), and have achieved accolades in the arts, including [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards), [Tony Awards](/Tony_Award), [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Award), and [Emmy Awards](/Emmy_Award). Notable alumni include a [U.S. President](/President_of_the_United_States), the current [Sovereign Prince of Monaco](/Monarchy_of_Monaco), two [Prime Ministers](/Prime_Minister_of_Greece) and one [Foreign Minister](/Minister_for_Foreign_Affairs_(Greece)) of Greece, a [President of Kenya](/President_of_Kenya), a [President of El Salvador](/President_of_El_Salvador), a [Chief Justice of the United States](/Chief_Justice_of_the_United_States), three [Speakers](/Speaker_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives) of the [U.S. House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives), a U.S. [Poet Laureate](/United_States_Poet_Laureate), the legal architect of the landmark decision in [Brown v. Board of Education](/Brown_v._Board_of_Education), and the inventor of the [blood bank](/Blood_bank). Amherst alumni have distinguished themselves as leaders in various fields, including science, religion, politics, the Peace Corps, medicine, law, education, communications, and business, as well as achieving acclaim as actors, architects, artists, astronauts, engineers, human rights activists, inventors, musicians, philanthropists, and writers.

Among its alumni, faculty, and affiliated individuals are six [Nobel Prize](/Nobel_Prize) laureates and twenty [Rhodes Scholars](/Rhodes_Scholarship). President [Calvin Coolidge](/Calvin_Coolidge), Chief Justice [Harlan F. Stone](/Harlan_F._Stone), and numerous other distinguished writers, academics, politicians, entertainers, businesspeople, and activists are among the college's esteemed graduates.

With approximately 23,000 living alumni, about 45% make an annual financial contribution to Amherst, representing one of the highest alumni participation rates among colleges nationwide. This strong alumni engagement underscores the enduring connection and loyalty fostered by the institution.

